<|startoftext|>Headline:"Clinton, Ohio Trump supporters vow to go 'above and beyond' for Ohio"
Content: "LANSER, Ohio (Reuters) - A U.S. presidential campaign rally in Cleveland on Friday to urge voters to keep up the momentum of Donald Trump s insurgent campaign, was in reference to the state of Ohio, in a state that is a key bell-weather political battle in the contest, Trump said. Kasich has no chance of winning the state, and Trump, the front-runner for the Republican nomination of the 2016 presidential race against Ohio Gov. John Kasich, has little chance of winning Ohio, where the Buckeye State is home to a large and prosperous county. Kasich is running in a closely-watched race in the state, while Trump, the last known candidate of the three hopefuls, has more opportunities for Ohio voters. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton called the primary vote in the state, which includes two large urban areas, a pivotal battleground, to give the voters of Ohio a glimpse into the presidential race. � The campaign is committed to going above and beyond any one person  and not blaming the Ohio situation,” Hillary Clinton told supporters at a campaign stop in the city. “What we want to say to our friends across the region and Ohio: Ohio is going to hold up and win as long as you use the vote. We just need to take one vote here, use it and don t take back up,” Clinton said. “Every vote counts,” Trump said. He added: “Just don t blame others for bad numbers like Ohio. It’s got to be Ohio.” Supporters of Kasich and Kasich said it will be hard to get Republican voters in Ohio, which went Republican in the 2012 presidential election, to follow through on the challenge. Kasich is a popular governor whose endorsement could open a path for him to win his party in Ohio, which has a large share of the Republican electorate and is home to a large population of Ohioans. Kasich is one of Trump s closest rivals for the nomination in the race; Kasich has said many polls have shown that he is better equipped to deal with the Republican nominee than his son. Kasich was expected to win at least one primary vote, meaning he likely has the money to spend in Ohio. Kasich’s supporters are hoping for a big turnout in the state. Clinton and her husband, Chelsea, had visited Cincinnati earlier this month, as the party waited for Trump and his supporters to rally the state before the May 14 primary. Clinton’s campaign did not immediately respond to requests for comment. U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Bernie Sanders, a Vermont senator, also endorsed Kasich. Sanders will be joined by U.S. Vice President Joe Biden in Ohio on Tuesday, but has already ruled out a Kasich endorsement and will likely be the first Democratic governor for Ohio next year. ",<|endoftext|>
